=3D"clean-btn tocCollapsibleButton_TO0P">On this page</button></div><div cl=
ass=3D"theme-doc-markdown markdown"><h1>Bayesian networks - an introduction=
</h1><p>This article provides a general introduction to Bayesian networks.<=
/p><h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"what-are-bayesian=
-networks">What are Bayesian networks?<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https:=
//www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#what-are-bayesia=
n-networks" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>Bayesian =
networks are a type of <strong>Probabilistic Graphical Model</strong> that =
can be used to build models from data and/or expert opinion.</p><p>They can=
 be used for a wide range of tasks including diagnostics, reasoning, causal=
 modeling, decision making under uncertainty, anomaly detection, automated =
insight and prediction.  </p><p>Figure 1 below shows these capabilities in =
terms of the four major analytics disciplines, <strong>Descriptive analytic=
s</strong>,
<strong>Diagnostic analytics</strong>, <strong>Predictive analytics</strong=
> and <strong>Prescriptive analytics</strong>, plus <strong>Causal AI</stro=
ng>.</p><p><img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Descriptive, predictive &amp;amp; p=
rescriptive analytics" src=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/assets/image=
s/analytics-9d60f27bab76d3f24a7b75487488d349.png" width=3D"1854" height=3D"=
952" class=3D"img_ev3q"></p><p>Figure 1 - Descriptive, diagnostic, predicti=
ve &amp; prescriptive analytics with Bayesian networks</p><div class=3D"the=
me-admonition theme-admonition-info alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div=
 class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg =
viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.=
56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7z=
M7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6=
v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0Q=
G"><p>They are also commonly referred to as <strong>Bayes nets</strong>, <s=
trong>Belief networks</strong>,  <strong>Causal networks</strong> and <stro=
ng>Causal models</strong>. </p></div></div><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithSt=
ickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"probabilistic">Probabilistic<a class=3D"hash-link" h=
ref=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#pro=
babilistic" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>Bayesian =
networks are probabilistic because they are built from probability distribu=
tions and also use the laws of probability
for <strong>Reasoning</strong>, <a href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs=
/techniques/diagnostics">Diagnostics</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.bayesserve=
r.com/docs/causality/causal-inference">Causal AI</a>, <a href=3D"https://ww=
w.bayesserver.com/docs/techniques/decision-automation">Decision making unde=
r uncertainty</a>, and more.</p><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_=
LWe7" id=3D"graphical">Graphical<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.=
bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#graphical" title=3D"Di=
rect link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>Bayesian networks can be depicte=
d graphically as shown in <em>Figure 2</em>, which shows the well known <em=
>Asia network</em>.
Although visualizing the structure of a Bayesian network is optional, it is=
 a great way to understand a model. </p><p><img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Asi=
a network" src=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/assets/images/asia-anima=
ted-19a40b3ec76bae1088c18cc05b14a60a.gif" width=3D"610" height=3D"470" clas=
s=3D"img_ev3q"></p><p>Figure 2 - A simple Bayesian network, known as the As=
ia network.</p><p>A Bayesian network is a graph which is made up of <strong=
>Nodes</strong> and directed <strong>Links</strong> between them.</p><h2 cl=
ass=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"nodes">Nodes<a class=3D"ha=
sh-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-net=
works/#nodes" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>In the =
majority of Bayesian networks, each node represents a <strong>Variable</str=
ong> such as someone's height,
age or country. A variable might be discrete, such as Country =3D {US, UK, =
etc...} or
might be continuous such as someone's age. </p><blockquote><p>In Bayes Serv=
er each node can contain multiple variables.  We call nodes with more than =
one variable <strong>multi-variable nodes</strong>.</p></blockquote><p>The =
nodes and links form the structure of the Bayesian network, and we call thi=
s the <strong>structural specification</strong>.</p><p>Bayes Server support=
s both discrete and continuous variables as well as function nodes.</p><h3 =
class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"discrete">Discrete<a cla=
ss=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/baye=
sian-networks/#discrete" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3=
><p>A discrete variable is one with a set of mutually exclusive states such=
 as Country =3D {US, UK, Japan, etc...}. </p><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWith=
StickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"continuous">Continuous<a class=3D"hash-link" href=
=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#contin=
uous" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>Bayes Server su=
pport continuous variables with <strong>Conditional Linear Gaussian distrib=
utions</strong> (CLG).  This simply means that continuous distributions can=
 depend on each other (are multivariate) and can also depend
on one or more discrete variables.</p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-=
admonition-info alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonition=
Heading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16=
"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7=
-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0=
 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></s=
vg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Although Gauss=
ians may seem restrictive at first, in fact CLG distributions can model com=
plex non-linear (even hierarchical) relationships in data.  Bayes Server al=
so supports <strong>Latent variables</strong> which can model hidden relati=
onships (automatic feature extraction, similar to hidden layers in a Deep n=
eural network).</p></div></div><p><img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Waste networ=
k" src=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/assets/images/waste-animated-41e=
06c0b8e55ea33df40d6344eea4dd0.gif" width=3D"668" height=3D"395" class=3D"im=
g_ev3q"></p><p>Figure 3 - A simple Bayesian network with both discrete and =
continuous variables, known as the Waste network.</p><h2 class=3D"anchor an=
chorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"links">Links<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D=
"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#links" ti=
tle=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>Links are added between=
 nodes to indicate that one node directly influences the
other. When a link does not exist between two nodes, this does not mean tha=
t they are
completely independent, as they may be connected via other nodes. They may =
however
become dependent or independent depending on the evidence that is set on ot=
her nodes.</p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert al=
ert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span clas=
s=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"eve=
nodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1=
 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7=
-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div=
 class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Although links in a Bayesian network a=
re directed, information can flow both ways (according to strict rules desc=
ribed later).</p></div></div><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe=
7" id=3D"structural-learning">Structural learning<a class=3D"hash-link" hre=
f=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#struc=
tural-learning" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>Bayes=
 Server includes a number of different  <a href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.=
com/docs/learning/structural-learning">Structural learning</a> algorithms f=
or Bayesian networks, which can automatically
determine the required links from data.</p><div class=3D"theme-admonition t=
heme-admonition-info alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admon=
itionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 =
14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.5=
6 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4=
.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></pat=
h></svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Note that=
 structural learning is not always  required, as often networks are build f=
rom expert opinion, and there are also many well known structures (such as =
mixture models) that can be used for certain problems.  </p></div></div><di=
v class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert alert--info admonit=
ion_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIc=
on_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3=
c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.5=
6-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H=
6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonit=
ionContent_S0QG"><p>Another useful technique is to make use of <strong>Late=
nt variables</strong> to automatically extract features as part of the mode=
l. </p></div></div><h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"d=
irected-acyclic-graph-dag">Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)<a class=3D"hash-lin=
k" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/=
#directed-acyclic-graph-dag" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a>=
</h2><p>A Bayesian network is a type of graph called a <strong>Directed Acy=
clic Graph</strong> or <strong>DAG</strong>.  A Dag is a graph with directe=
d links and one which
contains no directed cycles.  </p><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavba=
r_LWe7" id=3D"directed-cycles">Directed cycles<a class=3D"hash-link" href=
=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#direct=
ed-cycles" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>A directed=
 cycle in a graph is a path starting and ending at the same node where the =
path taken can only be along the direction of links.</p><h2 class=3D"anchor=
 anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"notation">Notation<a class=3D"hash-link=
" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#=
notation" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>At this poi=
nt it is useful to introduce some simple mathematical notation for variable=
s and probability distributions.</p><p>Variables are represented with upper=
-case letters (A,B,C) and their values with lower-case letters (a,b,c). If =
A =3D a we say that A has been instantiated.</p><p>A set of variables is de=
noted by a bold upper-case letter (<strong>X</strong>), and a particular in=
stantiation by a bold lower-case letter (<strong>x</strong>). For example i=
f <strong>X</strong> represents
the variables A,B,C then <strong>x</strong> is the instantiation a,b,c. The=
 number of variables in <strong>X</strong> is denoted |<strong>X</strong>|.
The number of possible states of a discrete variable A is denoted |A|.</p><=
p>The notation pa(X) is used to refer to the parents of X in a graph.  For =
example in <strong>Figure 2</strong>, pa(Dyspnea) =3D (Tuberculosis or Canc=
er, Has Bronchitis).</p><p>We use P(A) to denote the probability of A.</p><=
p>We use P(A,B) to denote the joint probability of A and B.</p><p>We use P(=
A | B) to denote the conditional probability of A given B.</p><h2 class=3D"=
anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"probability">Probability<a class=
=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesi=
an-networks/#probability" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h=
2><p>P(A) is used to denote the probability of A.  For example if A is disc=
rete with states {True, False} then P(A) might
equal <!-- -->[0.2, 0.8]<!-- -->.  I.e. 20% chance of being True, 80% chanc=
e of being False.</p><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D=
"joint-probability">Joint probability<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https:/=
/www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#joint-probability=
" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>A joint probability=
 refers to the probability of more than one variable occurring together, su=
ch as the probability of A and B, denoted P(A,B). </p><p>An example joint p=
robability distribution for variables <strong>Raining</strong> ad <strong>W=
indy</strong> is shown below.
For example, the probability of it being windy and not raining is 0.16 (or =
16%). </p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert alert-=
-info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D=
"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd=
