ty" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>Conditional proba=
bility is the probability of a variable (or set of variables) given another=
 variable (or set of variables), denoted P(A|B).</p><p>For example, the pro=
bability of Windy being True, given that Raining is True might equal 50%. <=
/p><p>This would be denoted P(Windy =3D True | Raining =3D True) =3D 50%.</=
p><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"marginal-probabili=
ty">Marginal probability<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesser=
ver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#marginal-probability" title=3D=
"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>A marginal probability is a d=
istribution formed by calculating the subset of a larger probability distri=
bution. </p><p>If we have a joint distribution P(Raining, Windy) and someon=
e asks us what is the probability of it raining,
we need P(Raining), not P(Raining, Windy). In order to calculate P(Raining)=
, we can simply sum up all the values for Raining =3D False, and Raining =
=3D True, as shown below. </p><p><img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Marginalizati=
on" src=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/assets/images/marginalization-2=
0c128ddec3619386f75d73dd52882e6.png" width=3D"633" height=3D"356" class=3D"=
img_ev3q"></p><p>This process is called <strong>marginalization</strong>.</=
p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert alert--info ad=
monition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonit=
ionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M=
7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.1=
4 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7z=
m1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"ad=
monitionContent_S0QG"><p>When we query a node in a Bayesian network, the re=
sult is often referred to as the <strong>marginal</strong>.</p></div></div>=
<div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert alert--info admo=
nition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitio=
nIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 =
2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 =
2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1=
 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admo=
nitionContent_S0QG"><p>For discrete variables we sum, whereas for continuou=
s variables we integrate.</p></div></div><div class=3D"theme-admonition the=
me-admonition-info alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonit=
ionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14=
 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 =
5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.1=
4 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path>=
</svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>The term ma=
rginal is thought to have arisen because joint probability tables written i=
n ledgers were summed along rows or columns, and the result written in the =
margins of the ledger. </p></div></div><p>A more complicated example involv=
ing the marginalization of more than one variable is shown below.</p><p><im=
g loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Multivariate marginalization" src=3D"https://www.=
bayesserver.com/docs/assets/images/marginalization-multi-dcff2fb7b2b4a4ed97=
e5124154da4caf.png" width=3D"586" height=3D"553" class=3D"img_ev3q"></p><h2=
 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"distributions">Distribu=
tions<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introd=
uction/bayesian-networks/#distributions" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=
=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>Once the structure has been defined (i.e. nodes and li=
nks), a Bayesian network requires a probability distribution to be assigned=
 to each node.</p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info aler=
t alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span =
class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D=
"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0=
 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14=
 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div>=
<div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Note that it is a bit more complic=
ated for time series nodes and noisy nodes as they typically require multip=
le distributions.</p></div></div><p>Each node X in a Bayesian network requi=
res a probability distribution P(X | pa(X)).</p><div class=3D"theme-admonit=
ion theme-admonition-info alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"=
admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D=
"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7=
s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 =
1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z">=
</path></svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Note=
 that if a node X has no parents pa(X) is empty, and the required distribut=
ion is just P(X) sometimes referred to as the prior. </p></div></div><p>Thi=
s is the probability of itself given its parent nodes. So for
example, in figure 2, the node Dyspnea has two parents (Tuberculosis or Can=
cer,
Has Bronchitis), and therefore requires the probability distribution P ( Dy=
spnea
| Tuberculosis or Cancer, Has Bronchitis ) an example of which is shown in =
table 1.
This type of probability distribution is known as a conditional probability=
 distribution,
and for discrete variables, each row will sum to 1.</p><p>The direction of =
a link in a Bayesian network alone, does not restrict the flow
of information from one node to another or back again, however does change =
the probability
distributions required, since as described above, a node's distribution is =
conditional
on its parents.</p><table><thead><tr><th align=3D"center">Has Bronchitis</t=
h><th align=3D"center">Tuberculosis or Cancer</th><th align=3D"center">Dysp=
nea =3D True</th><th align=3D"center">Dyspnea =3D False</th></tr></thead><t=
body><tr><td align=3D"center">True</td><td align=3D"center">True</td><td al=
ign=3D"center">0.9</td><td align=3D"center">0.1</td></tr><tr><td align=3D"c=
enter">True</td><td align=3D"center">False</td><td align=3D"center">0.8</td=
><td align=3D"center">0.2</td></tr><tr><td align=3D"center">False</td><td a=
lign=3D"center">True</td><td align=3D"center">0.7</td><td align=3D"center">=
0.3</td></tr><tr><td align=3D"center">False</td><td align=3D"center">False<=
/td><td align=3D"center">0.1</td><td align=3D"center">0.9</td></tr></tbody>=
</table><p>Table 1 - P ( Dyspnea | Tuberculosis or Cancer, Has Bronchitis )=
</p><p>Distributions in a Bayesian network can be <a href=3D"https://www.ba=
yesserver.com/docs/learning/parameter-learning">learned from data</a>, or s=
pecified manually
using expert opinion.</p><h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" i=
d=3D"parameter-learning">Parameter learning<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"h=
ttps://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#parameter-l=
earning" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>There are a =
number of ways to determine the required distributions.</p><ul><li>Learn th=
em from data</li><li>Manually specify (elicit) them using experts.</li><li>=
A mixture of both.</li></ul><p>Bayes Server includes an extremely flexible =
<strong>Parameter learning</strong> algorithm.  Features include:</p><ul><l=
i>Missing data fully supported</li><li>Support for both discrete and contin=
uous latent variables</li><li>Records can be weighted (e.g. 1000, or 0.2)</=
li><li>Some nodes can be learned whilst other are not</li><li>Priors are su=
pported</li><li>Multithreaded and/or distributed learning.</li></ul><p>Plea=
se see the <a href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/learning/parameter-l=
earning">parameter learning</a> help topic for more information.</p><h2 cla=
ss=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"online-learning">Online lea=
rning<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introd=
uction/bayesian-networks/#online-learning" title=3D"Direct link to heading"=
>=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>Online learning (also known as adaptation) with Bayes=
ian networks, enables the user or API developer to update the
distributions in a Bayesian network each record at a time.  This uses a ful=
ly Bayesian approach.</p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-in=
fo alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"=
><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-=
rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71=
 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7=
 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>inf=
o</div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Often a batch learning appr=
oach is used on historical data periodically, and an online algorithm is us=
ed to keep the model up to date in between batch learning.</p></div></div><=
p>For more information see <a href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/lear=
ning/online-learning">Online learning</a>.</p><h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWit=
hStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"evidence">Evidence<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"=
https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#evidence" =
title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>Things that we know (=
evidence) can be set on each node/variable in a Bayesian network.
For example, if we know that someone is a Smoker, we can set the
state of the Smoker node to True. Similarly, if a network
contained continuous variables, we could set evidence such as Age =3D 37.5.=
</p><p>We use <strong>e</strong> to denote evidence set on one or more vari=
ables. </p><p>When evidence is set on a probability distribution we can red=
uce the number of variables in the distribution, as certain variables then =
have known values
and hence are no longer variables.  This process is termed <strong>Instanti=
ation</strong>.</p><p>Bayes Server also supports a number of other techniqu=
es related to evidence:</p><ul><li><a href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/d=
ocs/analysis/evidence-optimization">Evidence optimization</a></li><li><a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/queries/retract-evidence">Retracted =
evidence</a></li><li><a href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/queries/so=
ft-evidence">Soft/virtual evidence</a></li></ul><h2 class=3D"anchor anchorW=
ithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"instantiation">Instantiation<a class=3D"hash-li=
nk" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks=
/#instantiation" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>The =
figure below shows an example of instantiating a variable in a discrete pro=
bability distribution.</p><p><img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Instantiation" sr=
c=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/assets/images/instantiation-3eadc9615=
0e6388a6cc32cf8e468d309.png" width=3D"804" height=3D"1068" class=3D"img_ev3=
q"></p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert alert--in=
fo admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"ad=
monitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=
=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c=
0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7=
-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div class=
=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Note that we can if necessary instantiate mo=
re than one variable at once, e.g. P(A=3DFalse, B=3DFalse, C, D) =3D&gt; P(=
C, D).</p></div></div><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info =
alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><s=
pan class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rul=
e=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.=
71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-=
3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</=
div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Note that when a probability d=
istribution is instantiated, it is no longer strictly a probability distrib=
ution, and is therefore often referred to as a <strong>likelihood</strong> =
denoted with the Greek symbol phi =CE=A6. </p></div></div><h2 class=3D"anch=
or anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"joint-probability-of-a-bayesian-netwo=
rk">Joint probability of a Bayesian network<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"h=
ttps://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#joint-proba=
bility-of-a-bayesian-network" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a=
></h2><p>If <strong>U</strong> =3D {A<sub>1</sub>,...,A<sub>n</sub>} is the=
 universe of variables (all the variables) in a Bayesian network,
and pa(A<sub>i</sub>) are the parents of A<sub>i</sub> then the joint proba=
bility distribution P(<strong>U</strong>) is the simply the product
of all the probability distributions (prior and conditional) in the network=
, as shown in the equation below.</p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-a=
dmonition-info alert alert--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionH=
eading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"=
><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-=
5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 =
8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></sv=
g></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>This equation i=
s known as the chain rule.</p></div></div><p><img loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"C=
hain rule for Bayesian networks" src=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/as=
sets/images/chain-rule-16bab14f620c4517032900bb15e86714.png" width=3D"497" =
height=3D"86" class=3D"img_ev3q"></p><p>From the joint distribution over <s=
trong>U</strong> we can in turn calculate any query we are interested in (w=
ith or without evidence set).</p><p>For example if <strong>U</strong> conta=
ins variables {A,B,C,D,E} we can calculate any of the following:</p><ul><li=
>P(A) or P(B), etc...</li><li>P(A,B)</li><li>P(A|B)</li><li>P(A,B|C,D)</li>=
<li>P(A | C=3DFalse)</li><li>...</li></ul><p>The problem is that joint prob=
ability distribution, particularly over discrete variables, can be very lar=
ge.</p><p>Consider a network with 30 binary discrete variables.  Binary sim=
ply means a variable has 2 states (e.g. True &amp; False).
The joint probability would require 2<sup>30</sup> entries which is a very =
large number.
This would not only require large amounts of memory but also queries would =
be slow.</p><div class=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert aler=
t--info admonition_LlT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=
=3D"admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"even=
odd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 =
1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-=
3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div =
class=3D"admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>Bayesian networks are a factorized repr=
esentation of the full joint.  (This just means that many of the values in =
the full joint can be computed from smaller distributions).  This property =
used in conjunction with the <strong>distributive law</strong> enable Bayes=
ian networks to query networks with thousands of nodes.</p></div></div><h2 =
class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"distributive-law">Distri=
butive law<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/i=
ntroduction/bayesian-networks/#distributive-law" title=3D"Direct link to he=
ading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>The <strong>Distributive law</strong> simply me=
ans that if we want to marginalize out the variable A we can perform the ca=
lculations on the subset of distributions that contain A</p><p><img loading=
=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Distributive law for Bayesian networks" src=3D"https://www=
.bayesserver.com/docs/assets/images/distributive-law-02291164e3dcb63497246f=
4d603eeeca.png" width=3D"495" height=3D"77" class=3D"img_ev3q"></p><div cla=
ss=3D"theme-admonition theme-admonition-info alert alert--info admonition_L=
lT9"><div class=3D"admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class=3D"admonitionIcon_kA=
Ly"><svg viewBox=3D"0 0 14 16"><path fill-rule=3D"evenodd" d=3D"M7 2.3c3.14=
 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7=
 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2=
V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z"></path></svg></span>info</div><div class=3D"admonitionCo=
ntent_S0QG"><p>The distributive law has far reaching implications for the e=
fficient querying of Bayesian networks, and underpins much of their power.<=
/p></div></div><h2 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"bayes=
-theorem">Bayes Theorem<a class=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserv=
er.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-networks/#bayes-theorem" title=3D"Direct =
link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>From the axioms of probability it is =
easy to derive Bayes Theorem as follows:</p><p>P(A,B) =3D P(A|B)P(B) =3D P(=
B|A)P(A) =3D&gt; P(A|B) =3D P(B|A)P(A) / P(B)</p><p>Bayes theorem allows us=
 to update our belief in a distribution <strong>Q</strong> (over one or mor=
e variables), in the light of new evidence <strong>e</strong>.
P(<strong>Q</strong>|<strong>e</strong>) =3D P(<strong>e</strong>|<strong>Q=
</strong>)P(<strong>Q</strong>) / P(<strong>e</strong>)</p><p>The term P(<s=
trong>Q</strong>) is called the prior or marginal probability of <strong>Q<=
/strong>, and P(<strong>Q</strong>|<strong>e</strong>)is called the posteri=
or probability of <strong>Q</strong>.</p><p>The term P(<strong>e</strong>) =
is the <strong>Probability of Evidence</strong>, and is simply a normalizat=
ion factor so that the resulting probability sums to 1.
The term P(<strong>e</strong>|<strong>Q</strong>) is sometimes called the l=
ikelihood of <strong>Q</strong> given <strong>e</strong>, denoted L(<strong=
>Q</strong>|<strong>e</strong>).
This is because, given that we know <strong>e</strong>, P(<strong>e</strong=
>|<strong>Q</strong>) is a measure of how likely it is that <strong>Q</stro=
ng> caused the evidence.</p><h3 class=3D"anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7=
" id=3D"are-bayesian-networks-bayesian">Are Bayesian networks Bayesian?<a c=
lass=3D"hash-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/ba=
yesian-networks/#are-bayesian-networks-bayesian" title=3D"Direct link to he=
ading">=E2=80=8B</a></h3><p>Yes and no.  They do make use of Bayes Theorem =
during inference, and typically use priors during batch parameter learning.
However they do not typically use a full Bayesian treatment in the <strong>=
Bayesian statistical</strong> sense (i.e. hyper parameters and learning cas=
e by case).</p><p>The matter is further confused, as Bayesian networks typi=
cally DO use a full Bayesian approach for <a href=3D"https://www.bayesserve=
r.com/docs/learning/online-learning">Online learning</a>.</p><h2 class=3D"a=
nchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id=3D"inference">Inference<a class=3D"ha=
sh-link" href=3D"https://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/bayesian-net=
works/#inference" title=3D"Direct link to heading">=E2=80=8B</a></h2><p>Inf=
erence is the process of calculating a probability distribution of interest=
 e.g. P(A | B=3DTrue), or P(A,B|C, D=3DTrue).
The terms inference and queries are used interchangeably. The following ter=
ms are all forms of inference will slightly difference
semantics.</p><ul><li>Prediction - focused around inferring outputs from in=
puts.</li><li>Diagnostics - inferring inputs from outputs.</li><li>Supervis=
ed anomaly detection - essentially the same as prediction</li><li>Unsupervi=
sed anomaly detection - inference is used to calculate the P(<strong>e</str=
ong>) or more commonly log(P(<strong>e</strong>)).</li><li>Decision making =
under uncertainty - optimization and inference combined.  See <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.bayesserver.com/docs/introduction/decision-graphs">Decision graph=
s</a> for more information.  </li></ul><p>A few examples of inference in pr=
actice:</p><ul><li>Given a number of symptoms, which diseases are most like=
ly?</li><li>How likely is it that a component will fail, given the current =
state of the system?</li><li>Given recent behavior of 2 stocks, how will th=
ey behave together for the next 5 time steps?</li></ul><div class=3D"theme-=
